Question 1

1.A

In question 1 we analyse and attempt to model temperatures at some weather stations in the Netherlands, using data from September 2019.

We convert the initial dataset into geodata object for better visualisation, since the dataset contained coordinates for the stations.

Fig 1: Tot Precipitations(mm) in September 2019 Netherlands Stations

From Figure 1 we can see that the total precipitation is higher at weather stations in the North, particularly in the North-East.

There is a fairly linear increase in precipitation with the increase in latitude, i.e.going further north in the map of the Dutch stations. This element is important and will have to be considered when fitting models that attempt to model this variable for the Dutch stations.

Fig 2: Overview of Characteristics of Dataset

Figure 2 confirms the positive linear relationship between precipitations and latitude. The precipitations totals dont appear to be normally distributed.

1.B

We select 5 stations at random and remove them from the training dataset, that we will use for fitting the models.

This step will be also useful when validating our models, since we will have residuals from the predictions to compare to the actual values and the models will be less biased.

Of course fitting the model using stations that might present different spatial characteristics, that is longitude and latitude, with respect to the stations we want to predict for can impact the predictions themselves, since distance is considered in both the variogram and Gaussian Process based on Maximum likelihood estimation.

1.C

The first method to model the data we will be using is Kriging based on variograms.

We obtain the sample variogram to the data.

sample_vario_precip <- variog(precip_data_train_geo, option = 'bin')

Fig 3: Raw Sample Variogram Precipitations Data

From the raw sample variogram we see that the partial sill starts to decline at higher distances, since there are fewer pairs of points in the bins.

But we know from geostatistical principles that the variance should increase as distance increases, therefore the variogram has to be modified.

We will set a maximum distance equal to 1.75, which is approximately the distance where the variance starts to decrease.

Fig 4: Sample Variogram with Defined Maximum Distance

We see indeed how the structure is now correct, with variances increasing with increase in distance between stations.

We also see from figure 4 the presence of a small nugget effect, which is the value of the variogram at zero distance. We will therefore set a nugget in the models we will estimate. This assumption can reduce slightly the correlation between adjacent stations.

By inserting a nugget we want to account for small scale variability, since two observations sampled closely will not always have the same value.

Presence of a nugget means that any two observations sampled arbitrarily closely will not necessarily have the same value.

Before fitting the models, we define the initial values to use in the optimization.

These are the partial sill, that is the difference between sill and nugget, and since for our case the nugget will be small it will be basically considered equal to the sill.From figure 4 we can see how this value can be considered to be 1750. Then we also set the initial value for range, which is the distance where the variogram starts to flatten out. This is an important element, since stations farther from the range will not present spatial autocorrelation.

We set the initial value for the range as 1.75.

ini_values_krig<-c(1750,1.75)

We fit a Parametric model, based on the variogram.

In the first model we define the nugget as equal to 2, and we leave the covariance function as the standard Matern with smoothness parameter kappa=0.5, so that we can have an initial idea of the fitting to the actual data and variogram.

## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
  krig_1 <- variofit(sample_vario_1,ini.cov.pars = ini_values_krig,fix.nugget=T,nugget=2)
  
estimated_parameters <- summary(krig_1)$estimated.pars
estimated_parameters

In particular here we have set the nugget, , as fixed, , is constant, while , the correlation range and , the partial sill or variance, have been directly estimated by the fitted model.

We try to improve the fit by changing covariance models.

First we use a spherical covariance function, leaving all the other assumptions and estimated parameters equal.

krig_2 <- variofit(sample_vario_1,ini.cov.pars = ini_values_krig,fix.nugget=T,nugget=2,cov.model = "spherical")

Then we fit another model with covariance function being power, and smoothness parameter kappa equal to 0.5.

krig_3 <- variofit(sample_vario_1, nugget = 2, cov.model = "power", fix.nugget = TRUE, ini.cov.pars = ini_values_krig,kappa=0.5)

Fig 5: Visual Comparison Variogram/Kriging Models

1.D

In part D we want to use Gaussian process model fitted using maximum likelihood, to estimate the parameters.

We will use for optimization the same initial values that we defined previously and the fixed nugget, since we have seen in the previous part that there was a small nugget effect in the data.

The models will all be fitted on the training dataset, that includes 95 stations.

model_lik_1<- likfit(precip_data_train_geo, ini.cov.pars =ini_values_krig,trend="1st",lik.method="ML",cov.model="matern",fix.nugget=T,nugget=2)

The first model includes also a linear trend for the mean function, since we have seen the presence of such trend in the initial data analysis.

The covariance function used in the first attempt to model is the Matern.

We then change the covariance function, using the spherical in the second model, leaving the other assumptions unchanged.

model_lik_2<- likfit(precip_data_train_geo, ini.cov.pars =ini_values_krig,trend="1st",lik.method="ML",cov.model="spherical",fix.nugget=T,nugget=2)

Since there are many options in terms covariance models to be used, and relative smoothness parameter kappa, we define a function that loops over the different covariance functions, and kappa values from 0.5 to 2.

The function calculates the AIC and log likelihood for each model and returns the model with the lowest AIC and highest log likelihood, which should indicate a better fit and therefore considered a better model.

cov_models <- c("matern", "exponential", "gaussian", "spherical", "circular", 
                "cubic", "wave", "powered.exponential", "cauchy",  "gneiting")
kappa_values <- c(0.5, 1, 1.5, 2) 

estimate_model <- function(data, cov_models, kappa_values = NULL) {
  best_model <- NULL
  best_aic <- Inf
  best_log_likelihood <- -Inf
  
  for (cov_model in cov_models) {
    for (kappa in kappa_values) {
      # Estimate model parameters
      model <- likfit(data, ini.cov.pars = ini_values_krig, trend = "1st",
                      lik.method = "REML", cov.model = cov_model, fix.nugget = TRUE,
                      nugget = 2, kappa = kappa)
      
      # Calculate AIC
      aic <- AIC(model)
      
      # Calculate log-likelihood
      log_likelihood <- logLik(model)
      
      # Update best model
      if (aic < best_aic || (aic == best_aic && log_likelihood > best_log_likelihood)) {
        best_model <- model
        best_aic <- aic
        best_log_likelihood <- log_likelihood
        best_cov_model <- cov_model
        best_kappa <- kappa
      }
    }
  }
  
  cat("Best Covariance Model:", best_cov_model, "\n")
  cat("Best Kappa Value:", best_kappa, "\n")
  cat("\n")
  
  return(best_model)
}
  


# Estimate the best model
best_model <- estimate_model(precip_data_train_geo, cov_models, kappa_values)

The model with the lowest AIC and highest Log likelihood is the model with covariance function defined with powered exponential and kappa equal to 0.5.

We will therefore fit this model and assess its goodness.

model_lik_best<- likfit(precip_data_train_geo, ini.cov.pars =ini_values_krig,trend="1st",lik.method="REML",cov.model="powered.exponential",fix.nugget=T,nugget=2,kappa=0.5)

We compare the fitted models based on AIC ,Log Likelihood and Mean Absolute Error.

1.E

In this part of question 1 we will use the Bayesian Approach to estimate the parameters.

The model is set so to have a powered exponential covariance function, since this was the covariance function of the best Gaussian Process estimated with MLE.

In the model control we also define a mean function with linear trend.

We define the prior for the correlation length parameter, based on the estimated values for this parameters from the previous model, therefore the discrete prior will have a range from 0.2 to 1.1.

For the nugget we define a range from 0 to 2, since we considered the nugget effect very small but present. We set the bins so that we optimize the trade-off between precision and efficiency of running and producing output from the model, since the model has to sample to produce the posterior distribution for the parameters of interest.

The priors for both the correlation length and the nugget parameters are set as reciprocal , so that the prior belief is for these parameters is to have a higher probability of taking smaller values and lower of taking larger values.

Since we have limited knowledge about the parameters and we consider their range to be comprised by small values, based on the previous analysis, this seems a reasonable, even if not completely precise, choice.

bayes_precip <- krige.bayes(
  geodata = precip_data_train_geo, 
  loc = ex.grid, 
  model = model.control(
    trend.d = "1st",
    trend.l = "1st", 
    cov.model = "powered.exponential"
  ),
  prior = prior.control(
    phi.discrete = seq(0.2, 1.1, l = 20),
    phi.prior = "reciprocal", 
    tausq.rel.prior = "reciprocal", 
    tausq.rel.discrete = seq(0, 2, l = 50)
  )
)

2.B

To study and model the data, we limit the dataset under analysis to data from 1990 onward.

The time series from 1990 seems to be not stationary.

We check this using the Augmented Dickey-Fuller and the KPSS tests.

print(p_value, digits = 16)
## [1] 0.01
print(p_value_kpss, digits=16)
## [1] 0.01

The null hypothesis is of stationarity for the first test and the opposite for the KPSS test.

The small p-values indicate rejection of the null for both tests, and mixing results in terms of proved stationarity of the time series.

Since we still presume non-stationarity we will calculate the difference of the time series. This differenced series shows much more stationary and stable behaviour. Assuring stationarity of the time series is a necessary step to fit ARIMA and ARMA models.

Fig 9: Acf and Pacf Differenced Monthly Anomaly

From figure 9 ,that shows the ACF and PACF of the differenced time series, we see significant lags 1 and 3.

After having differenced the time series to make it stationary, we will fit Arima and then ARMA models, without seasonal components, and compare them based on AIC and Log Likelihood values. The model with the best metrics and reasonable residuals will be chosen for forecasting out of the sample.

We first use auto.arima that automatically searches for the best Arima model, we set the maximum difference equal to 1, since taking the first difference of the original time series was enough to make it stationary.

arima_auto <- auto.arima(surf_temp_recent_ts,max.d=1, seasonal = FALSE,include.mean=T)

Only the AR(2) term of this model resulted as significant.

Having noticed significant spikes at lag 1 and 3 for the ACF and PACF , shown in figure 9 , of the differenced time series, we will fit first ARIMA(3,1,3) with drift included.

arima_2<-Arima(surf_temp_recent_ts,order=c(3,1,3),include.drift=T)

Then an ARIMA(1,1,3)

arima_3<-Arima(surf_temp_recent_ts,order=c(1,1,3),include.drift=T)

And also an ARIMA(3,1,1)

arima_4<-Arima(surf_temp_recent_ts,order=c(3,1,1),include.drift=T)

Finally, since the most significant lag in the ACF and PACF was the first one we will try fitting also an ARIMA(1,1,1).

arima_5<-Arima(surf_temp_recent_ts,order=c(1,1,1),include.drift=T)

The Arima models are fitted on the original time series, and the model definition applies the first difference, since d=1.

Then we fit ARMA models. In this case the models are fitted to the differenced time series.

The first ARMA is defined with 1 autoregressive and 1 moving average term since the most significant lag in the ACF and PACF was lag 1.

arma_1 <- Arima(diff(surf_temp_recent_ts),order=c(1,0,1),include.drift=T)

Since it is not always possible to assess the correct moving average and autoregressive terms for an ARMA model just by analyzing the ACF and Pacf, we want to fit models with different terms to see if the fit can be improved.

We fit an ARMA(2,0,1).

arma_2 <- Arima(diff(surf_temp_recent_ts),order=c(2,0,1))

And then,an ARMA(4,0,3), to see if adding parameters can improve the fit, even if this can lead to potential overfitting.

 arma_3 <- Arima(diff(surf_temp_recent_ts),order=c(4,0,3))

We now compare the ARIMA and ARMA models to decide which one is the best.

2.C

In Part C we consider the same dataset used for part B, but we aggregate the original data , using monthly means, in quarterly data.

Taking the first difference makes the time series more stationary.

The analysis of the differenced time series with seasonality at lag 4(since we use quarterly data), shows lack of stationarity.

The ACF and PACF of the differenced quarterly time series, shows no clear indication of which terms should be included in the first SARIMA model ,therefore we will start with a simple model that has 1 moving average term both in the non-seasonal and seasonal part.

The full model is a SARIMA(0,1,1, 0,1,1).

The model includes a seasonal difference to account for the lack of stationarity in the differenced time series with seasonality at lag 4.

model_seas <- Arima(surf_temp_quart_ts,
                    order = c(0, 1, 1),                
                    seasonal = list(order = c(0, 1, 1), 
                                    period = 4))

We compare this model with the choice of auto.arima with seasonal component, which gives a SARIMA(0,1,0, 1,0,1) not differencing on the seasonal part.

auto_seas<-auto.arima(surf_temp_quart_ts,seasonal=T)

We then create a function that loops over different autoregressive and moving average terms for both the not-seasonal and the seasonal part.

The function considers 1 difference for both parts, based on the reasons explained previously, and tries to find the model with the lowest AIC.

d <- 1
D <-1
s <- 4
results <- data.frame()

for(p in 1:4) {
  for(q in 1:4) {
    for(P in 1:4) {
      for(Q in 1:4) {
        if(p + d + q + P + D + Q <= 12) {
          model <- Arima(surf_temp_quart_ts, order = c(p-1, d, q-1),include.drift =T, seasonal = list(order = c(P-1, D, Q-1), period = s))
          test <- Box.test(residuals(model), lag = log(length(residuals(model))))
          sse <- sum(residuals(model)^2)
          results <- rbind(results, c(p-1, q-1, P-1, Q-1, model$aic, sse, test$p.value))
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

colnames(results) <- c("p", "q", "P", "Q", "AIC", "SSE", "BoxTestPValue")
results <- as.data.frame(results)
results$AIC <- as.numeric(as.character(results$AIC))
results$SSE <- as.numeric(as.character(results$SSE))
results$BoxTestPValue <- as.numeric(as.character(results$BoxTestPValue))


best_model <- results[which.min(results$AIC),]

cat("Best model parameters:\n")

2.D

In part D we fit two Dynamic Linear Models with linear trend and respectively, quarterly and monthly seasonality.

The first one will be fit on the quarterly time series.

For the first model we have to estimate the variance of the observation noise, and the variances of the state equation for both the linear and the seasonal part.

We create a function to define these parameters and a matrix with zeros, elsewhere. We will then estimate the parameters using Maximum Likelihood.

The initial values for the 3 parameters will be set as 0.

  Dlm_lin_quart <- function(x) {
    dlmModPoly(order = 2, dV = exp(x[1]), dW = c(0, exp(x[2]))) +
      dlmModSeas(frequency = 4, dV = 0, dW = c(exp(x[3]), rep(0,2)))
  }

Mle_lin_quart <- dlmMLE(surf_temp_quart_ts, parm = c(0,0,0), build =Dlm_lin_quart)

We check that convergence has been reached.

# check convergence 
Mle_lin_quart$convergence
## [1] 0

We then apply the Kalman filter to the fitted model. This will update and filter the estimate of the state variables at each time step, based on new observations.

# Kalman filter
fitted_model_lin_quart <-Dlm_lin_quart(Mle_lin_quart$par)
surf_temp_quart_lin <- dlmFilter(surf_temp_quart_ts, mod = fitted_model_lin_quart)

We then fit a Dlm model on the monthly time series.

This model will have monthly seasonality and linear trend.

The parameters to estimate are still the 3 variances, for which the initial values will be set as 0.

Dlm_lin_monthly <- function(x) {
  dlmModPoly(order = 2, dV = exp(x[1]), dW = c(0, exp(x[2]))) +
    dlmModSeas(frequency = 12, dV = 0, dW = c(exp(x[3]), rep(0, 10)))  
}

# Initial params 
initial_params <- c(0, 0, 0)

# Fit the model with Mle 
Mle_lin_monthly <- dlmMLE(surf_temp_recent_ts, parm = initial_params, build = Dlm_lin_monthly)

We check also in this case convergence.

Mle_lin_monthly$convergence
## [1] 0

And finally we apply the Kalman filter to the fitted model.

# Kalman filter
fitted_model_lin_monthly <- Dlm_lin_monthly(Mle_lin_monthly$par)
lin_monthly_surf<- dlmFilter(surf_temp_recent_ts, mod=fitted_model_lin_monthly )

We now compare the two DLMs based on Mean Squared Error, Mean Absolute Deviation,Mean Absolute Percentage Error,all calculated on the models residuals. Furthermore we make the comparison based also on Log Likelihood and especially AIC.

The residuals of the best model seem autocorrelated and dont explain all the variability in the data, but the same was true for the residuals of the other DLM.

Figure 15: Forecast Best DLM Model

We see from figures 13-15, how, while, the Arima models predict a decrease or a constant level in anomaly for global surface temperature, the best Dlm model predicts a continuation of the upward trend, so it is close to the actual trend of the studied time series.

It is important to remember how the best way to really assess the forecasts produced by these models would be to compare them with the actual values for 2024, which we dont have.

Figures 11-13 and, also the not perfect residuals, show the possibility to further improve the models to better capture the trends and variability in the time series.

3.A

In this question we will model the maximum daily temperatures for some weather stations in UK for 2022.

We first analyze the weather stations in terms of their presence in the UK territory and based on their elevation.

Fig 16 : UK Weather Stations by Elevation

The stations present similar elevation, excluding a couple of outliers.

They are concentrated in the South-East of UK, with the exception being Fair Isle, in Scotland, and other in the middle of the UK territory.

Since the elevation doesnt differ much, the main elements for the spatial analysis will be the longitude and latitude coordinates.

Fig 17: Time Series of Max Temperature 2022 UK Stations

The time series of maximum temperatures, shown in figure 17, clearly displays the expected pattern in maximum daily temperature, with increase from January and peak in July and then decrease until the end of the year, typical seasonal variation.

There are some differences between the stations, since some are more in the North of UK, like Fair Isle, but overall they follow the same pattern.

It is clear from this plot how it wont be useful to analyze the maximum temperature using data from periods far apart from each other.

In this part we want to fit a Gaussian Process to predict the maximum temperature for 3 stations on the 24th of July.

We first merge the spatial dataset with the dataset containing maximum daily temperatures for the stations.

We then select and keep only data until the 24th of July, to avoid look-ahead bias, and since we want to forecast for July, we subset the dataset to contain data only from the 23th of June until the 23th of July.

We exclude the 3 stations we want to predict for from the training dataset.

We fit a Gaussian Regression process to the training dataset.

We dont include station elevation since we analyzed the data and saw how it didnt change or differ a lot for the majority of stations.

We use the squared exponential kernel since we want to model a non linear complex relationship.

We also specify the initial value for the noise variance parameter, based on the variance in the observed temperatures in the training set.

# Predictor and response  
X <- train_data_gp_clean[, c("station_longitude", "station_latitude", "station_elevation")]
y <- train_data_gp_clean$temperature


gp_model <- gausspr(X, y, kernel = "rbfdot", fit.method = "mle",var=25)

We then predict the temperature for the 24th of July for the 3 stations using the fitted model.

predicted_temperatures <- predict(gp_model, test_data_try)

mod_arima_fair <- Arima(fair_isle_train, order = c(3, 1, 0))
